### GET request with a header
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/ip
Accept: application/json

###
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/get
    ?generated-in=IntelliJ IDEA

### GET request with parameter
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/get?show_env=1
Accept: application/json

### GET request with environment variables
//TIP <p>Press <shortcut actionId="GotoDeclaration"/> on <b>{{show_env}}</b> to navigate to declaration</p>
//TIP <p>Putting <i>scheme:// + host</i> to <b>{{host}}</b> allows switching schemes between different environments</p>
GET {{host}}/get?show_env={{show_env}}
Accept: application/json

### GET request with disabled redirects
# @no-redirect
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/status/301

### GET request without cookies
# @no-cookie-jar
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/cookies

### The request will be sent as is, without encoding
# @no-auto-encoding
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/anything?value=@+$!

### GET request with cookie passed through headers
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/cookies
Cookie: theme=darcula; last_searched_location=IJburg

### GET request with dynamic variables
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/anything?id={{$random.uuid}}&ts={{$timestamp}}

### Define own filename for saved response file
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/get

//TIP File will be named <i>my-response.json</i> instead of default name
>> {{$historyFolder}}/my-response.json

### Force own filename for saved response file
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/get

//TIP If there is already a <i>my-forced-response.json</i>, HTTP Client will override it
>>! {{$historyFolder}}/my-forced-response.json

### GET request with HTTP/2 protocol
GET https://examples.http-client.intellij.net/get HTTP/2
